# healthchecks.io ping config for bin/cron-run.sh and bin/push-web-data.sh.
#
# Copy to cron/healthchecks.env (gitignored) ON THE SERVER and fill in. When
# this file is absent, the cron wrappers skip pinging entirely — so local/dev
# checkouts need no config and the cron jobs behave exactly as before.
#
# Each cron job pings the slug-based endpoint twice per run:
#   https://hc-ping.com/<key>/<slug>/start          before the job runs
#   https://hc-ping.com/<key>/<slug>/<exit-code>?create=1   after it finishes
# where <slug> is the job's log-name (e.g. observe-buses) and <exit-code> is
# its exit status (0 = success, non-zero = failure, so a job that runs but
# crashes alerts too). The start/finish pair lets healthchecks measure and
# chart each job's run DURATION. The healthchecks.io dashboard is the
# at-a-glance "what ran recently / how long it took / what's overdue" board, and
# alerting (email, ntfy, Slack, webhook, …) is wired per-project in its UI —
# nothing to run or host yourself.
#
# Note on the free tier: it keeps the last 100 events per check, and each run is
# 2 events (start + finish). So duration HISTORY is a rolling window (~50 min for
# the every-minute canary, days for the slow jobs) — the latest run duration is
# always shown; only deep history is truncated. Bump to a paid tier for 1000.
#
# The cron wrappers append ?create=1 to each ping (healthchecks
# "auto-provisioning"): the FIRST ping for a slug auto-creates its check, and the
# parameter is a no-op once the check exists. Auto-created checks start with
# defaults of period 1 day / grace 1 hour / all integrations on — those CANNOT
# be set via the ping URL, so tune each check's period + grace in the dashboard
# (or the Management API) after it first appears.
#
# NOT every cron job pings: only the curated HC_MONITORED set in bin/cron-run.sh.
# Single-agency bus-only roster is 9 jobs — well under the free tier's 20-check
# cap, so everything except the low-stakes weekly/monthly recap is watched.
# Widen/narrow by editing HC_MONITORED in bin/cron-run.sh.
#
# Setup (one time):
#   1. Create a healthchecks.io project. Copy its "Ping key" (Project Settings
#      -> API Access) into HC_PING_KEY below — the only secret pinging needs.
#   2. Over the next cron minutes the monitored jobs auto-appear on the
#      dashboard. Set each check's Period + Grace to match its cadence (suggested
#      values below; the 1d/1h defaults are too loose) and attach a notification
#      channel.
#
# Suggested period / grace (period = cadence; grace = lateness tolerance before
# it pages). Because we send a /start ping, GRACE MUST ALSO EXCEED THE JOB'S RUN
# DURATION: healthchecks marks a check down if the finish ping doesn't arrive
# within grace of the start. Most jobs finish in seconds so this never bites —
# except bus-speedmap (~1h runtime).
#   observe-buses                period 1m,  grace 7m   (every-minute canary)
#   bus-bunching / bus-cross-bunching / bus-gaps   period 20m, grace 15m
#   bus-thin-gaps                period 15m, grace 15m
#   bus-ghosts / audit-alerts    period 1h,  grace 20m  (hourly / :30)
#   bus-speedmap                 period 2h,  grace 90m  (~1h runtime — grace must exceed it)
#   fetch-gtfs                   period 1d,  grace 2h   (daily 03:15)

# Project ping key from healthchecks.io (Project Settings -> API Access ->
# "Ping key"). The only secret needed for slug-based pinging.
HC_PING_KEY=replace-with-your-healthchecks-ping-key

# Ping base URL. Defaults to the hosted service; override only for self-hosted.
# HC_PING_URL=https://hc-ping.com
